===Etymology===
From {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{term|Philistinus|lang=la}}, from Late {{etyl|grc|en}} {{term|Φυλιστῖνοι|lang=grc}}, from {{etyl|he|en}} {{term|פְּלִשְׁתִּים|tr=p'lishtím|lang=he}}, from {{term|פְּלֶשֶׁת||Philistia|tr=p'léshet|lang=he}}.

The sense relating to lack of education and culture was introduced to English by [[w:Thomas Carlyle|Thomas Carlyle]] and greatly popularised by [[w:Matthew Arnold|Matthew Arnold]]. It is derived from {{etyl|de|en}} student use of the term {{term|Philister||lang=de}} to refer to the burghers of the town. This apparently derived from the use of the biblical text "the Philistines be upon you, Samson" in a memorial service for a Jena university student who died as the result of a [[w:Town and gown|town versus gown]] dispute in 1693.

